                                <div class="column-block">
                                    <div class="column">
                                        <p>When someone close to you dies the impact is multi-faceted. The first and most obvious issue which you’ll have to deal with will be the emotions you’ll feel. No two people are exactly the same, and so the grief, anger, sadness and shock will differ from person to person and case to case. The important thing to realise is that there’s no such thing as the ‘right’ way to feel when you lose a loved one, and that the cliché about time being a great healer is actually based on truth. Although it’s difficult to believe in the immediate aftermath of a death, there will come a time when you can look back on the life of that person with joy as well as sadness. </p>
                                        <p>The second aspect of bereavement, and one which may come as more of a shock, is the sheer number of practical matters which have to be dealt with. In some cases the deceased may have engaged in a degree of pre-planning for their funeral, but this is often not the case, particularly if the death was unexpected. Even pre-planning will leave some aspects of the process, such as registering the death, to be handled after the event, and dealing with the wide range of different bodies involved can seem overwhelming. </p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="column">
                                        <img src="~/images/video.jpg" alt="">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="padding-left">
                                    <p>Burialplots.co.uk was created, in part, to make the impact of bereavement a little less overwhelming. We do this, initially, by making it much easier to find and purchase a burial plot in the UK. The existing burial plot market place isn’t working properly, with demand outstripping supply and prices rising ever higher. We’ve utilised the latest technology to make finding a plot in your favoured location quick and simple, and we also offer payment plans to increase flexibility and affordability.</p>
                                    <p>The second aspect of our offer is access to the full range of services needed when arranging a funeral. Whether you utilise a funeral director or arrange the details yourself, you’ll find links, advice and help across our website. We’ve pulled together all of the services you might be interested in, as well as a range of advice on legal and emotional matters, and the details of organisations which specialise in helping people cope with bereavement.</p>
                                    <p>Although every funeral is a reflection of the individual who’s been lost and the feelings of those left behind, there are certain aspects which the majority of funerals tend to involve, and links to bodies which provide those services can be found across the site. As well as funeral directors, we provide the general details on aspects such as choosing a coffin, arranging a memorial, booking the cars needed for a funeral, the kind of flowers which you might wish to purchase and the funeral plan options which are available. It may well be the case that the time and trouble involved in arranging the funeral for a loved one leads you to decide that you want to spare those close to you from going through the same process by arranging your own funeral in advance.</p>
                                    <p>No matter what your individual circumstances are, you’ll find everything you need to cope with bereavement within Burialplots.co.uk. If you have any questions, or would like to discuss something you’ve seen on the site,  then please email us at (Email) or call our team on 0100 000 0000.</p>
                                </div>
                                <br />
                                <h2 class="underline">Probate Services</h2>
                                <div class="padding-left">
                                    <p>If you’ve agreed to execute a will and feel that the task is simply too complicated to handle, or that you can’t spare the time and effort involved, then you may wish to enlist the aid of a professional probate service. A probate service of this kind is generally offered by a solicitor or accountant, although there are some firms which run as dedicated probate specialists. All will charge a fee for handling probate, and it is best to shop around to get the best fee possible. Some specialists, for example, offer an estimated fee which may rise higher as the process develops, whilst others work for a fixed percentage of the value of the estate. It may seem simpler to work with the solicitors who drew up or stored the will, but there is no obligation to do so, and you may be able to find a better deal elsewhere. </p>
                                </div>
                                <br />
                                <h2 class="underline">Type of Service</h2>
                                <div class="padding-left">
                                    <p>Depending upon the complexity of the estate in question you may opt for either of two types of service, a Full Estate Administration or a Grant Only service. A Full Estate Administration service will deal with all aspects of probate on your behalf, from valuing the estate through preparing all necessary paperwork and paying liabilities to distributing the estate to the beneficiaries. A Grant Only probate service will expect you to gather all the relevant information regarding the estate, after which they will prepare the necessary paperwork and gain the grant of representation.  The grant will then be given to you, enabling you to deal with the estate. If you use a Grant Only service you will save money in fees but bear full responsibility for aspects such as finalising the tax position, paying taxes and distributing the estate.</p>
                                    <p>Planning carefully in advance can minimise the complexity and stress of estate management, as can accessing the correct services following a death. For advice on either of these, contact us at (Email) or by calling 0100 000 0000.</p>
                                </div>

